[1] American Samoa: Measles vaccination campaign
Date: Wed 1 Jan 2020
Source: VaxBefore Travel [abridged, edited]
https://www.vaxbeforetravel.com/american-samoa-measles-virus-cases-were-due-genotype-b3


The Pacific country of American Samoa announced it is continuing its measles virus vaccination campaign, which focuses on immunizing all school-aged children.

According to a Situation Report published on 30 Dec 2019, about 98 percent of American Samoa children (12 months -- 18 years old) have received the 1st dose of the measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine, and 90 percent of these children have completed the 2nd recommended dose of MMR.

On 11 Dec 2019, American Samoa began its campaign to vaccinate all adults with no evidence of the MMR vaccine.

To date, 12 152 MMR doses have been administered to adults 19 years and older. The total number of measles cases since the outbreak began includes 10 laboratory-confirmed via RT-PCR testing at Hawaii State Lab, and 4 suspected cases with laboratory results pending.

All positive cases were due to measles virus genotype B3.

The rash onset date for the last laboratory-confirmed measles case is 7 Dec 2019. This is important because the outbreak declaration will be lifted after 2 incubation periods (42 days from 7 Dec 2019) without another laboratory-confirmed measles case.

American Samoa is a separate, unincorporated territory of the United States, with a population of about 55 000 residents. It is located in the South Pacific Ocean, southeast of the independent nation of Samoa, and is centered on 14.2710 deg S, 170.1322 deg. W.

American Samoa consists of 5 main islands and 2 coral atolls. The largest and most populous island is Tutuila. Recent measles outbreaks in the western Pacific and Oceana area include the following: Australia, Fiji, Samoa.

[Byline: Dani Reiter]

